### 4. Aggregated SNP Hashes (ASH)
* **Presenter:** Tony Przygienda
* **Slides:** [04-ash-00](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-lsr-ash-00-00)
* **Discussion:**
  * **Summary:** Formerly known as the "Merkle tree" proposal, the draft has been renamed to Aggregated SNP Hashes (ASH). It addresses database synchronization inefficiencies on very large link-state databases.
  * **Technical Details:**
    * Aligns with the classic CSNP/PSNP structure by introducing Complete ASH (CAsh) and Partial ASH (PAsh) packets.
    * Migrated the hashing algorithm to 64-bit SipHash-1-3 to prevent database-wide hash collisions.
    * Simulations on a database of 1 million fragments with 50,000 nodes demonstrated that 64-bit SipHash prevents collisions over a 64-year operational span.
    * Testing showed a 35% packet savings in small databases (3k fragments) and up to a 92% reduction in CSNP/PSNP overhead in massive databases (100k fragments) during steady-state synchronization.
  * **Questions and Comments:**
    * **Acee Lindem** clarified that the 92% savings represents a reduction in total PDUs transmitted relative to standard CSNP runs.
    * **Chris Hopps** asked about the churn model used for simulations. Tony Przygienda explained the model simulates periodic LSP lifetime refreshes alongside a 1–2% hourly churn rate mimicking real-world link flaps and metrics updates.

